The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson sparked a major shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is a participant in the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What’s more, it’s the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or “less bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it’s not entirely clear that it’s Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still lacking to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can meet in the same place and at the same time.
According to The Particle Adventure website of Berkeley Laboratories that, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature are propagated and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I would underline here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if he manages to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily trivial boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it it requires reaching extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN (the big hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself glued to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
What can all these investigations "provide"? asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of the MS.
For their part, many fervently want them to meet, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we haven’t found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are hard to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong in saying it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution their work would bring about.
They saw the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Just imagine...
And in addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this pickup now serves as an "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That’s not to say, of course, that the LHC’s activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
