Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", used to advance a video game and which can be won by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both bookkeepers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are in the public ledger, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown to computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a phase of file splitting, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "cutting" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (plus zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split in two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the one hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins on deposit have been stolen.
“The failure used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Heavy actors such as Wikipedia reject such payments.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, the "giant sales" were launched.
“$30,000 was exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Their system, Paytunia, equates to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier also manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, should this currency succeed.
