A constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using an interim text, repeatedly modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial turmoil.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delusion” and continues to “betray his word” and “treat the law.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis faster and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as the controversy wreaks havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this resource has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "Either they vote for my text or I retain the full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in the vast majority, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted were unanimous.
The commentators are pleased, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all eyes, remains finally identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm his or her compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of liberals are also heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on that text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
“We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule on all of this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy remains and henceforth insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to go on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
