For now, this sector of the economy has hardly been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday". That day, in the United States began the orgy of sales that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by clashes.
That day, some workers at the Walmart Corporation, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, abandoned their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside unions and left-wing activists in the stores of the corporation, whose products target people with modest and moderate incomes.
Walmart sells everything from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those in larger supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid Walmart workers buy only at work.
The availability and assortment of products have made Walmart one of the largest corporations in America.
In the words of two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at very low prices, in part because it pays its workers little.
The latter also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or handheld scanners.
That "Black Friday" rally participants demanded increased wages and complained that the cost of the health insurance provided by the corporation went from $30 to $100 per month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who receives $9.5 an hour, this expense is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 an hour, it will cost the corporation $3.2 trillion.
This is about 1.1% more than what you spend on wages now.
If Walmart puts the pay rise on consumers’ shoulders, each visit to the store will cost them only 46 cents more.
In one year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they spend now.
Supporters of Walmart are pleased that the protest took place in only nine states and did not cause any loss to the corporation.
Black Friday lasted in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the following day, and during that time, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers carried out the "Black Friday" almost 100 million transactions.
The company’s representative, Dan Fogelman, said in an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post that “fewer than five” Walmart employees left their jobs and that the protest had been “another PR stunt” organized by the workers’ union.
"Free box!"
