We began to address the problems of reproduction in space with the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments with plants were carried out.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then came the breeding of insects in orbit, small fruit flies, the Drosophila.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent to the space to check how the embryo develops under conditions of weightlessness.
As a result, we get a normal chick.
But then the problems begin.
