Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized in a different way?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) acts there, with an organization similar to ours, with a college too, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also somewhat analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organisation, the courts of account are even at this level, and in this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to draw a comparison without concrete data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to specify exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
Of course not, but I don’t like to make that kind of comparison.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model have to face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, you wouldn't benefit from working with our office, would you?
As far as the legislation of our country is concerned, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office?
Given that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet manifested itself in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is seen in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in the field of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to tighten the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path takes us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA1>varc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it prohibits anything, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office which has the obligation to carry out such checks and to demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but you can't say we'll do as if nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
