Architecture studio MVRDV proves that true adventures are not just in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "mountain of books"- 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by passing through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "Also, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one enters these old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, boasts the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictional bridges that appear represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policymakers decided that there was only one way to improve the statistics: we had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar charts and responsible for funny as well as cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for Spijkenisse’s mountain of books, the so-called ‘Boekenberg’.”
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain rises at the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and semi-detached buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the “Dutch National Wood Award 2012”.
In this way, the small town lacking history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather guess a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese tree.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with their topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the annealed brick floor and the elegant streetlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
As you look up you can see the park benches, dogs and children playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Usually the book shelves are arranged along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade and in the center opens a huge dark room which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is put up the classic spatial configuration and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that take on the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And this is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a few millimeters thick plastic fabric has been used as the basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafe you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but also in it you can enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the appropriate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge crystal pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden trusses located transverse to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Likewise, the professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain connection with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved great success in that discipline that in specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany said it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status at the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, due to the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to prove its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is.
This is because he is currently reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a US-led policy, so to speak, and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already begun the path towards a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries such as France or Great Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for this reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful and not alienate itself from Arab public opinion nor from the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it that much importance since it is not a completely one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by refraining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic break as in the case of Libya.
This may have earned Germany some respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
Instead, the U.S. has been clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I think that the real disparity of opinions does not really have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to take a European stance.
Of course this is not at all easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it has with Israel.
This has always been a pelagic topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take on a leading role?
Or maybe you still find it hard to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it continues to be difficult for the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as a leading actor, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and is that no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way, Germany finds itself in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The U.S. influence on European politics is diminishing more and more, but the EU does not fill that void at the moment, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more prominent role.
Even if they don't like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular people, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren too.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the real eponyms do not file a claim.
And even then it’s not clear that they’re going to be right.
“Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the firm Taylor Wessing, which specializes in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada he registers Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company applied to register Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying mark.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
“It’s harmful to the business, you have to fight it,” Pattloch demands.
"The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors concerned are millionaires, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros a year, China is, in size, the third largest market for luxury goods and the one that grows at the fastest pace.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of doubtful legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name object of the lawsuit had already become a “market reality.”
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged the plaintiff's trademark in China," Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphical elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely initially used a blue-and-white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the labor emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain pending.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usual in China, the numbers are surprising.
Last year, CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means China leads the list of new enrollments worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg demonstrates.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the impersonator has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
Freudenberg was right in the next two instances, but the opposing party is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
The case has now reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending a decision.
Wentzler hoped to be able to resolve the issue favourably and praised the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to one hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly settlement, but was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
in particular if the imitators secure there the rights over unprotected trademarks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial field, but managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” says Wentzler.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend German companies to be extremely prudent when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international law on trademark rights, but what must be done is “to register also in China everything that may be susceptible to protection”, as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: dancing, singing, helping
In Heidelberg the choir Imbongi rehearses and in Swaziland the AIDS orphans rejoice
The story of a link capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers away.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, heels and loafers look for the compass on the parquet floor, and quickly find it.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the voices of the singers (alt, bass, tenor and soprano) slowly begin to rise, swirling, numbing and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to get out of his box almost by trying to put order with his energetic and gentle gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg the Imbongi choir rehearses a new song.
Fifty singers, aged between 23 and 69, from the human geneticist to the homeowner have also arrived.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each voice of the choir has a different text and also in a foreign language barely known: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS Programme, there are approximately 34 million people infected with HIV worldwide.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV-positive.
The Voices for Africa association has found sponsors in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans of the village of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover the school’s tuition, uniform and will guarantee you a hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means in Zulu "storyteller" or "panegirist".
In this room no one knows how to speak this Bantu language fluently, but singing does.
For ten years this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
At 8,733 kilometers away in a straight line from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a village called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected.
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large part of them are children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what affects Swaziland: the highest AIDS infection rate and the lowest life expectancy worldwide, according to UNICEF.
The population does not see circumcision as a good thing, a practice that has been shown to halve the risk of contagion.
More than 40 percent of Swaziland’s population carries the immunodeficiency virus, and dying in their early thirties has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir discovered this secluded population, but what they saw above all were many children on the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school degree, the possibilities in a poor country are more than sparse.
At first it was only the particular commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa" which has since professionally dealt with AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs of viral origin are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Lads and scabies are among parasite-borne STDs.
What are the main groups of affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are most common in men who have sex with other men.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, at least four out of every five cases of syphilis registered in Germany have their origin in sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20 per cent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
Approximately 2,700 cases were recorded in 2011.
That’s one-tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, flow, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore are not detected.
How can one be protected?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through dirt infections and through physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend undergoing regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, the fees charged by the choir for its performances throughout Germany, they raise a lot of money.
"In total, we have already sent some 200,000 euros to Esitjeni," said Annette Lennartz, president of the association.
In the village itself, Zodwa Dlamini, a self-confident woman with leadership skills, manages the money sent from Germany.
He takes care of the orphans finding a good accommodation, for example with one of the grandmothers.
The "gogos", as older women are called in Zulu, are the pillars of the people.
Some of them have up to 14 orphans in their care, offer them a roof where to live and take care of the children to go to school every day on time and dressed in their uniforms.
Those who have no one are under the protection of Khanyisile, a single woman who, like the two cooks who cook every day for more than 200 hungry children, receives a salary from the association.
In addition, Voices of Africa has set up a sewing school, built two chicken coops and, in collaboration with the American health organization PSI, has managed to get many of the villagers tested for HIV.
This is not obvious, since, despite the fact that this disease is evident throughout the country, it is not usually openly spoken of.
A king with 14 wives
“AIDS is an absolute taboo,” says Annette Lennartz, “because it has to do with sexuality.”
Something strange in a country where the king officially has 14 wives.
Black Africa’s last absolute monarch, King Mswati III, is known for his opulent and overwhelmed lifestyle.
Polygamy instead of democracy.
This officially unaccepted way of life is largely responsible for the rapid spread of the HIV virus in recent decades.
But it is also due to the innumerable seasons that travel the country from one side to the other and take it wherever they go.
According to Annette Lennartz, "free condoms can be bought in any corner, but these are barely used.
It’s another culture, here they only accept skin-to-skin contact.”
To foster cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two to three years through southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, combative spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost tip of the African continent still remember from the era of apartheid.
A bus full of whites singing songs in a language of blacks; so much recognition not only brings with it an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but it has also managed to tear off a couple of tears from some rabid border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Esitzheni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Although this small town barely appears on maps, in the valley of the Ezulweni River it is well known.
"Come to Esitzheni, there shines the light," the locals say.
And after travelling the 8,733 kilometers in a straight line back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms on Bergheimer Street full of singers marking the step, one realizes that it is also possible to see its light shining from there.
