The tour of the mountainous region of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus proceeds with great bang through the winding road that passes alongside wooded hills, high-flow rivers and the simple homes of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, one might even think that it is located in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
The Talyshi people live here, a village of which not much is known, apart from the fact that they perfectly master Persian and Azeri and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts an architecture perhaps too massive designed in the Soviet era and that does not seem to fit completely in such a picturesque mountainous landscape.
European tourists hardly get to this place, as the road from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate the two urban centers, it takes eight hours because the road is one-way.
The amazing wealth that the country enjoys thanks to the oil of the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilate Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
“Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will celebrate the Festival of the World’s Oldest People,” says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one in the world.
Here is documented the life of eight dozen talyshis of the place who have exceeded 100 years of age. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
His son died at the age of 136.
However, the undisputed star of the museum is sheepshepherd <0xC5><0x9E>irali Müslümov, who seems to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate that certifies this.
And if we take into account that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov’s age is quite suspicious.
“He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973,” Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children, and apparently still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Has <0xC5><0x9E>irali Müslümov been wrong at his age in a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard about the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
“In some regions of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan very old people also live,” Scholz says, “even in Sardinia there are many older men.”
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific evidence about age, especially when there is no civil record.
