The Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway’s five million people enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country’s success bears any relation to its greed for an extremely smelly fish?
Take a series of overcured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, damp football clothing.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of the delicacies of Norway.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It is snowy. The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how smelly you prefer it.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink,” says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the “General of Rakfisk,” who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking from a drink significant amounts of the drink.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Havard.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I'll try a few bits.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, it’s not bad; it’s not much different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few miles by bus.
The rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, in which poverty plagued Norway and in which, before there was refrigeration, the fish was stored during the autumn immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, an essential, though rather smelly, part of Norway’s past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be purchased.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A cane of beer or a sandwich cost you a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 event.”
Norwegians find it very hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway’s current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she passes rakfisk trays and with her long blonde hair and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, wise people.”
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything, except a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn’t have during the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a laughing shred.
I'm in the snow lining up to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is definitely something different and quite succulent to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a bow tie presenter who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe they're the fumes of all that fish.
