Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of Bradley Manning abuse during his time in prison
Trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution’s pre-trial interrogation of Manning in Ft. Meade, Maryland, U.S. Attorney Commander Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits by officers from the unit that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defense’s request to dismiss the case because his incarceration had been harsh and it had already meant enough punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning reviewed the forms that officers filled out after Manning’s visits during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the caretakers as “excellent” and the treatment received at the facility in general as “very professional.”
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that visiting officers had spoken about those issues and indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
“They wrote ‘no incidents’ (after they had talked about the issues) but that doesn’t necessarily mean I wouldn’t have mentioned any issues,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the January 2011 meeting with a board tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was under.
The military said it had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of other people.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the caretakers could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he made in Thursday's statement that after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of caretakers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge’s interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the watchman’s order that he should drop the blanket he might have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but that he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted at the war council, which is scheduled to start early next year.
The defense said it plans to make Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules applicable to any detainee in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted on all charges, he could face life in prison.
