And they are?
In the weeks of uncertainty following the Colorado vote to legalize possession of small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the response in hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of misdemeanors for marijuana possession are being overturned both here and in the state of Washington, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped filing charges against those over 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legally passed once the law enters into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s most conservative districts have pledged to move forward with cases opened for marijuana possession and are still citing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent recently authorized marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“All of this is changing so quickly that I don’t know what the next thing is going to be,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police at Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those in charge of regulations in the state of Washington are also turning the issue around.
And they continue to seek advice on establishing a system of production, manufacturing, distribution and sales licenses, all before the deadline of 1 December 2013.
