In addition, there are some delicate mechanical issues that need to be resolved during that period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state’s requirement to offer “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana and its ban on conducting cannabis businesses within 300 meters of schools, parks, children’s playgrounds or children’s centers.
“Nowhere will it be harder to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” says Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently created research group.
On November 21, Aurora’s police chief, Oates, sent an email to his police officers informing them that the city’s prosecutor would stop prosecuting minor misdemeanors for possession of marijuana by people over the age of 21 and that police would stop bringing charges against those crimes “with immediate effect.”
Police Chief Oates said they would enforce the city’s regulations regulating the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and would continue to pursue drug dealers and sellers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to pursue marijuana possession cases, mainly to pressure consumers and to decide to receive treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
“Our office has an obligation to bring legal action against those misdeeds that at the time they occurred were a crime,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana legalization initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
Pete Hautzinger, the county district attorney, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes,” he said.
Even though 55 percent of voters supported the measure, it was never considered that bringing recreational marijuana use into the government and judicial system would be easy.
The contradictory reactions that arise throughout the state show a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the great ecological experiment in this state.
“This is a cultural barrier to district attorneys,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney representing marijuana possession defendants and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
