As the first states to consider small amounts of marijuana in the same way as if it were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become the national test cases for drug legalization.
While lawyers and state officials have a new legal sales frontier, they also look forward to receiving guidance from the federal government, which still envisages considering the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal offenses.
Advocates of marijuana legalization hope the Department of Justice will give in.
Although there have been some prominent arrests of patients and marijuana vendors for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has mostly allowed marijuana sales businesses to exist for these purposes in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
“While anti-drug agents are likely not to pull down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they will likely be reluctant to allow the operation of state-regulated stores for the sale of recreational marijuana, permitted under the new law,” said Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
