Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed until I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory"
Students are not attacked for their views just now
I don’t remember any time in my life that I haven’t been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue the History career, I had already packed up, triggering the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started crying.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had quit because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson announced jokingly that I had left because I was forced to drink in peeled cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my extravagant name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the conservative party.
You may be wondering what that's coming for now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students is such in Oxford that last week a group of them called for the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's JCR (Grade Student Group) say they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as non-grateful people" for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college’s Equal Opportunity Committee to make sure they can express their views freely.
His situation was not favored by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics that portrayed the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated like "Turkish heads" by introducing higher tuition rates.
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing leftist trend in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old Corpus Christi history student who introduced the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, 19, and elected president of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first weeks at Oxford I was more alone than at one.
I went to college in September 1986, I was an 18-year-old who was terribly shy.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at its highest.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny former student Margaret Thatcher an “honoris causa” degree following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that not only did the professors turn a blind eye to the mockery of the conservative university students, but they gladly participated in it.
The policy of the miners’ strike, the privatization and the government’s opposition to the apartheid sanctions in South Africa went all the way to the seminary’s wooden halls.
The first time I attended, French texts from the eighteenth century were to be translated into English, and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
Not one of them.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew how to expel bad bile.
"Are the Thatcherists refusing to learn French, or are they simply fools?" he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning from the tears I was trying to contain.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your free time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt grunted.
I went back to my room like a soul in pain.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how it goes.
They mess with anyone who's suspected of being Tory.
For me it's very complicated, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it'll be even worse.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labour.”
Later, at a local pub, I cowardly tried to cover it up.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick turned out to be useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted this song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do the Tories have sex?" one asked.
“They beat each other up, don’t they?”
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could you someday lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to stay with people who thought like me only after dark?
Should I become Labour and repress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history assigned to my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative Party, but also Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote him his speeches.
I was barely there.
He hated the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist vision of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I began commuting daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude.”
Her sore eyes began to get cloudy.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to make a joke.
It would break my heart if you left it.”
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and had renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of history had hinted, speaking totally seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “stupid old men.”
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my university career in Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my persecutors gave up.
When they left I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me weak crying.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only formed 14 Prime Ministers of the Conservative Party but, to this day, hides behind a reputation unearned by equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety"
