The World's Toughest Craft: Kawah Ijen's Human Mules
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano play life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is a hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the innards of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with air.
After plucking large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle pace, keeping the balance and temptingly measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the cliff.
They know that any trip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who broke down years ago because of the risks of the Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine
Once upstairs, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euros) for every kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
“As is normal to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually carries three times a day.
It takes three hours in each and ends up ground, but they allow you to raise 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn on the field.
"The miners' pay is very high here, where the coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)", clarifies the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the tago was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town close to the volcano, for a weighty reason that, in Indonesia, is as blunt as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and is irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing with his skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already started to take a toll on him despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
You have asthma, have difficulty breathing, cough constantly, and are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
It’s the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this sympathetic and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater and lights up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he has bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its small profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at both weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) camera surcharge that, together with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old porter who has been in Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, she says she will endure working "as much as she can" because she needs the money to educate her three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulphur burns the throat and darkens the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases ... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pains and shoulder sores, which have been malformed by the weight.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions pluck 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat path through the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: that of the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
